<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The family 
<taxonomicName family="Shiraiaceae" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="family">Shiraiaceae</taxonomicName>
was introduced by 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.11646/phytotaxa.103.1.4" author="Liu, YX" journalOrPublisher="Phytotaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="51 - 60" refId="B34" refString="Liu, YX, Hyde, KD, Ariyawansa, HA, Li, WJ, Zhou, DQ, Yang, YL, Chen, YM, Liu, ZY, 2013. Shiraiaceae, new family of Pleosporales (Dothideomycetes, Ascomycota). . Phytotaxa 103: 51 - 60" title="Shiraiaceae, new family of Pleosporales (Dothideomycetes, Ascomycota)." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/phytotaxa.103.1.4" volume="103" year="2013">Liu et al. (2013)</bibRefCitation>
with a single genus and later 
<taxonomicName class="Dothideomycetes" genus="Grandigallia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Grandigallia" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">Grandigallia</taxonomicName>
was added to this family by 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.11646/phytotaxa.147.2.1" author="Ariyawansa, HA" journalOrPublisher="Phytotaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="35 - 47" refId="B2" refString="Ariyawansa, HA, Kang, JC, Alias, SA, Chukeatirote, E, Hyde, KD, 2013. Towards a natural classification of Dothideomycetes: The genera Dermatodothella, Dothideopsella, Grandigallia, Hysteropeltella and Gloeodiscus (Dothideomycetesincertae sedis). . Phytotaxa 147: 35 - 47" title="Towards a natural classification of Dothideomycetes: The genera Dermatodothella, Dothideopsella, Grandigallia, Hysteropeltella and Gloeodiscus (Dothideomycetesincertae sedis)." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/phytotaxa.147.2.1" volume="147" year="2013">Ariyawansa et al. (2013)</bibRefCitation>
. In previous studies, 
<taxonomicName family="Shiraiaceae" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="family">Shiraiaceae</taxonomicName>
was closely related with 
<taxonomicName family="Phaeosphaeriaceae" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="family">Phaeosphaeriaceae</taxonomicName>
and their distinction was questionable (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1002/jobm.200410434" author="Cheng, TF" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Basic Microbiology" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="339 - 350" refId="B9" refString="Cheng, TF, Jia, XM, Ma, XH, Lin, HP, Zhao, YH, 2004. Phylogenetic study on Shiraiabambusicola by rDNA sequence analyses. . Journal of Basic Microbiology 44: 339 - 350" title="Phylogenetic study on Shiraiabambusicola by rDNA sequence analyses." url="https://doi.org/10.1002/jobm.200410434" volume="44" year="2004">Cheng et al. 2004</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.11646/phytotaxa.103.1.4" author="Liu, YX" journalOrPublisher="Phytotaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="51 - 60" refId="B34" refString="Liu, YX, Hyde, KD, Ariyawansa, HA, Li, WJ, Zhou, DQ, Yang, YL, Chen, YM, Liu, ZY, 2013. Shiraiaceae, new family of Pleosporales (Dothideomycetes, Ascomycota). . Phytotaxa 103: 51 - 60" title="Shiraiaceae, new family of Pleosporales (Dothideomycetes, Ascomycota)." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/phytotaxa.103.1.4" volume="103" year="2013">Liu et al. 2013</bibRefCitation>
). However, our multi-gene analyses (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Maximum likelihood phylogenetic tree generated from RAxML (GTR + G model), based on combined LSU, SSU, TEF 1 and RPB 2 sequences data. ML values (MLBP) (&gt; 50 %), resulting from 1000 bootstrap replicates and Bayesian posterior probabilities (BYPP) greater than 0.90, are given at the nodes. The original isolate numbers' codes are noted after the species names. The tree is rooted to Dothidea insculpta (CBS 189.58). Ex-type or ex-epitype strains are in bold. Newly generated strains are in red and the new genus is in yellow background." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.58.36723.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/329243" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
) clearly indicate that 
<taxonomicName family="Shiraiaceae" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="family">Shiraiaceae</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName family="Phaeosphaeriaceae" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="family">Phaeosphaeriaceae</taxonomicName>
are distinct. Evidence is also borne out by the fact the 
<taxonomicName family="Phaeosphaeriaceae" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="family">Phaeosphaeriaceae</taxonomicName>
have single ascostromata (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/s13225-014-0308-3" author="Phookamsak, R" journalOrPublisher="Fungal Diversity" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="159 - 238" refId="B44" refString="Phookamsak, R, Liu, JK, McKenzie, EHC, Manamgoda, DS, Ariyawansa, H, Thambugala, KM, Dai, DQ, Camporesi, E, Chukeatirote, E, Wijayawardene, NN, Bahkali, AH, Mortimer, PE, Xu, JC, Hyde, KD, 2014. Revision of Phaeosphaeriaceae. . Fungal Diversity 68: 159 - 238" title="Revision of Phaeosphaeriaceae." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s13225-014-0308-3" volume="68" year="2014">Phookamsak et al. 2014</bibRefCitation>
), while in 
<taxonomicName family="Shiraiaceae" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="family">Shiraiaceae</taxonomicName>
, ascostromata have multiple ascomata. Moreover, 
<taxonomicName family="Shiraiaceae" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="family">Shiraiaceae</taxonomicName>
produces a high quantity of hypocrellins and no such metabolites, secreted by 
<taxonomicName family="Phaeosphaeriaceae" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="family">Phaeosphaeriaceae</taxonomicName>
, were reported as far as we know (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/s13225-014-0308-3" author="Phookamsak, R" journalOrPublisher="Fungal Diversity" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="159 - 238" refId="B44" refString="Phookamsak, R, Liu, JK, McKenzie, EHC, Manamgoda, DS, Ariyawansa, H, Thambugala, KM, Dai, DQ, Camporesi, E, Chukeatirote, E, Wijayawardene, NN, Bahkali, AH, Mortimer, PE, Xu, JC, Hyde, KD, 2014. Revision of Phaeosphaeriaceae. . Fungal Diversity 68: 159 - 238" title="Revision of Phaeosphaeriaceae." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s13225-014-0308-3" volume="68" year="2014">Phookamsak et al. 2014</bibRefCitation>
). In this study, the third genus (i.e. 
<taxonomicName class="Dothideomycetes" family="Shiraiaceae" genus="Rubroshiraia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Rubroshiraia" order="Pleosporales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">Rubroshiraia</taxonomicName>
) is introduced to the family and produces hypocrellins. The endophytic strains in the phylogenetic tree in Figure (2) probably can be named as new genera, once the types are selected. Thus, currently three genera are placed in 
<taxonomicName family="Shiraiaceae" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="family">Shiraiaceae</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
